{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2015}} {{italic title}} [[File:Tampines Mall.JPG|thumb|right|Modern malls have been described as the new "cathedrals of consumption."<ref>{{cite news|last=Clay|first=Grady|title=Cathedrals of Consumption: The Malling of America|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/02/17/books/cathedrals-of-consumption.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 17, 1985}}</ref>]] '''''Homo consumericus''''' ([[mock Latin]] for consumerist person) is a [[neologism]] used in the social sciences, notably by [[Gad Saad]] in his book ''The Evolutionary Bases of Consumption''<ref>Gad Saad, ''The Evolutionary Bases of Consumption'' (Routledge, 2007) {{ISBN|0-8058-5149-6}}</ref> and by [[Gilles Lipovetsky]] in ''Le Bonheur Paradoxal''.<ref>Gilles Lipovetsky, ''Le bonheur paradoxal, Essai sur la société d'hyperconsommation'', (éditions Gallimard, 2006)</ref> According to these and other scholars the phenomenon of [[mass consumption]] could be compared to certain traits of human psychology described by [[Evolution theory|evolutionary scientists]] pointing out similarities between [[Darwinism|Darwinian]] principles and [[consumer behaviour]].<ref>[http://jmsb.concordia.ca/~GadSaad/Jill%20Sundie-%20Review%20of%20my%20book.pdf Jill M. Sundie 'Where is Homo Consumericus', Contemporary Psychology: APA Review of Books (2007) ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706173614/http://jmsb.concordia.ca/~GadSaad/Jill%20Sundie-%20Review%20of%20my%20book.pdf |date=July 6, 2011 }}</ref><ref>George Siomkos, 'Homo Consumericus: The Coming of the Post-Modern Consumer', Marketing Week , Special Issue No. 1.000, April 5, 2004</ref> Lipovetsky has noted that modern times have brought about the rise of a ''third'' type of ''Homo consumericus,'' who is unpredictable and insatiable.<ref>[http://weblogs.clarin.com/detrasdeltelon/archives/2007/11/acaba_de_editarse_en_espana.html Detrás del Telón – Homo Consumericus] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905063051/http://weblogs.clarin.com/detrasdeltelon/archives/2007/11/acaba_de_editarse_en_espana.html |date=September 5, 2008 }}</ref>
A similar expression "Homo Consumens" was used by [[Erich Fromm]] in ''Socialist Humanism'' , written in 1965.
